# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: opus-codec
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:opus-codec/celt] CELT was meant to bridge the gap between Vorbis and Speex for applications where both high quality audio and low delay are desired.
[src:opus-codec/celt] It is suitable for both speech and music.
[src:opus-codec/celt] It borrows ideas from the CELP algorithm, but avoids some of its limitations by operating in the frequency domain exclusively.
[src:opus-codec/celt] The original stand-alone CELT has been merged into Opus.
[src:opus-codec/celt] Therefore, CELT as stand-alone format is now abandoned and obsolete.
[src:opus-codec/celt] Development is going on only for its hybridised form as a layer of Opus, integrated with SILK.
[src:opus-codec/celt] This article covers the historic, stand-alone format; for the integrated form and its evolution since the integration into Opus see the article on Opus.
[src:opus-codec/celt] CELT's central feature is low algorithmic delay.
[src:opus-codec/celt] It allows for latencies of typically 3 to 9 ms but is configurable to below 2 ms at the price of more bitrate to reach a similar audio quality.
[src:opus-codec/celt] CELT supports mono and stereo audio and is applicable to both speech and music.
[src:opus-codec/celt] It can use a sampling rate from 32 kHz to 48 kHz and above and an adaptive bitrate from 24 kbit/s to 128 kbit/s per channel and above.
[src:opus-codec/celt] There are no known intellectual property issues pertaining to the CELT algorithm, and its reference implementation is published under a permissive open-source license (the 2-clause BSD).
[src:opus-codec/celt] Like Vorbis, CELT is a fullband (entire human hearing range) general-purpose codec, i.e. not specialized for special types of audio signals and therefore different from its sibling project Speex.
[src:opus-codec/celt] The format enables for transparent results at high bitrates, as well as very decent quality at lower bitrates.
[src:opus-codec/celt] All in all, the compression capabilities are said to be significantly superior to those of MP3, and as another useful feature for realtime applications like telephony, CELT's audio quality at lower bitrates are even on par with HE-AACv1, thanks to the band folding.
[src:opus-codec/celt] In comparative double-blind listening tests it proved to be noticeably superior to HE-AACv1 at ~64 kbit/s.
[src:opus-codec/celt] It has a comparably low computational complexity that resembles that of the low-delay variant of AAC (AAC-LD) and stays significantly below the complexity of Vorbis.
[src:opus-codec/celt] It enables for constant and variable bitrate.
[src:opus-codec/celt] If the signal disappears into the noise floor in speech pauses and similar cases, the transmission can be limited to signal the output of comfort noise to the decoder.
[src:opus-codec/celt] Most settings of the naturally streaming-enabled format can be changed on the fly without interrupting transmission.
[src:opus-codec/celt] The format is robust to transmission errors.
[src:opus-codec/celt] Loss of whole packets as well as bit errors can be masked with a steady degradation of audio quality (packet loss concealment, PLC).
[src:opus-codec/celt] CELT is a transform codec based on the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) and concepts from CELP (with a code book for excitation, but in the frequency domain).
[src:opus-codec/celt] The initial PCM-coded signal is handled in relatively small, overlapping blocks for the MDCT (window function) and transformed to frequency coefficients.
[src:opus-codec/celt] Choosing an especially short block size on the one hand enables for a low latency, but also leads to poor frequency resolution that has to be compensated.
[src:opus-codec/celt] For a further reduction of the algorithmic delay to the expense of a minor sacrifice in audio quality, the by nature 50% of overlap between the blocks is practically cut down to half by silencing the signal during one eight at both ends of a block, respectively.
[src:opus-codec/celt] The coefficients are grouped to resemble the critical bands of the human auditory system.
[src:opus-codec/celt] The entire amount of energy of each group is analysed and the values quantised for data reduction and compressed through prediction by only transmitting the difference to the predicted values (delta encoding).
[src:opus-codec/celt] The (unquantised) band energy values are removed from the raw DCT coefficients (normalisation).
[src:opus-codec/celt] The coefficients of the resulting residual signal (so-called “band shape”) are coded by Pyramid Vector Quantisation (PVQ, a spherical vector quantisation).
[src:opus-codec/celt] This encoding leads to code words of fixed (predictable) length, which in turn enables for robustness against bit errors and leaves no need for entropy encoding.
[src:opus-codec/celt] Finally, all output of the encoder are coded to one bitstream by a range encoder.
[src:opus-codec/celt] In connection with the PVQ, CELT uses a technique known as band folding, which delivers a similar effect to spectral band replication (SBR) by reusing coefficients of lower bands for higher ones, but has much less impact on the algorithmic delay and computational complexity than the SBR.
[src:opus-codec/celt] This works against “birdie” artifacts by preserving more richness in the appropriate frequency bands.
[src:opus-codec/celt] The decoder unpacks the individual components from the range coded bitstream, multiplies the band energy to the band shape coefficients and transforms them back (via iMDCT) to PCM data.
[src:opus-codec/celt] The individual blocks are rejoined using weighted overlap-add (WOLA).
[src:opus-codec/celt] Many parameters are not explicitly coded, but instead reconstructed by using the same functions as the encoder.
[src:opus-codec/celt] For the channel coupling CELT may use M/S stereo or intensity stereo.
[src:opus-codec/celt] Blocks can be described independent from adjacent frames (Intra-frame); for example to enable a decoder to jump into a running stream.
[src:opus-codec/celt] With transform codecs so-called pre-echo artifacts can get audible, because the quantisation error of sharp, energy-heavy sounds (transients) can spread over the entire DCT block and the transient doesn't mask them backward in time as well as forward.
[src:opus-codec/celt] With CELT each block can be further divided to thwart such artifacts.
[src:opus-codec/celt] First work on plans and drafts for a Vorbis successor was done in 2005 at Xiph.org as part of the Ghost project (initially talked about as “Vorbis II”).
[src:opus-codec/celt] This discussion together with Vorbis creator Christopher Montgomery led to Jean-Marc Valin′s interest in a particularly low-latency codec.
[src:opus-codec/celt] In December 2007, the first draft version of libcelt was published as version 0.0.1, initially named “Code-Excited Lapped Transform”.
[src:opus-codec/celt] CELT was established as an IETF technology in July 2009 under the "ietfcodec" working group.
[src:opus-codec/celt] In May 2009, a draft of *RTP payload format for the CELT Codec* was published.
[src:opus-codec/celt] In version 0.9, the pitch prediction operating in the frequency domain used until then was replaced by a less complex solution with a pre- and postfilter pair in time domain, which was contributed by Raymond Chen of Broadcom.
[src:opus-codec/celt] With CELT 0.11 from February 4, 2011 the format was tentatively frozen (“soft freeze”) – reserving the possibility of unexpectedly necessary last changes.
[src:opus-codec/celt] The draft for Opus has been registered at the IETF since September 2010.
[src:opus-codec/celt] The software library **libcelt** serves as the reference implementation for CELT, written in C and published as free software under Xiph's own 3-clause BSD-ish license.
[src:opus-codec/celt] Despite the format not being finally frozen, it was being used in many VoIP applications such as Ekiga and FreeSWITCH, which switched to CELT upon entering soft-freeze in January 2009, as well as Mumble, TeamSpeak and other software.
[src:opus-codec/celt] In April 2011, support for CELT was included in FFmpeg.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus combines the speech-oriented LPC-based SILK algorithm and the lower-latency MDCT-based CELT algorithm and pyramid vector quantization, switching between or combining them as needed.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Bitrate, audio bandwidth, complexity, and algorithm choice can be adjusted for each individual frame.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus has low algorithmic delay (26.5 ms by default) ideal for use as part of a real-time communication link, networked music performances, and live lip sync; by trading off quality or bitrate, the delay can be further reduced down to 5 ms.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Its delay thus is significantly lower compared to competing codecs, which require well over 100 ms.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus remains competitive with these formats in terms of quality per bitrate.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] As an open format standardized through RFC 6716, a reference implementation called *libopus* is available under the New BSD License.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The reference has both fixed-point and floating-point optimizations for low- and high-end devices, with SIMD optimizations on platforms that support them.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] All known software patents that cover Opus are licensed under royalty-free terms.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus is widely used as a voice over IP (VoIP) codec in applications such as Discord, WhatsApp, and the PlayStation 4.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Listening tests have ranked it higher-quality than other standard audio formats at any given bitrate until transparency is reached, including MP3, AAC, and HE-AAC.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus supports constant and variable bitrate encoding from 6 kbit/s to 510 kbit/s (or up to 256 kbit/s per channel for multi-channel tracks), frame sizes from 2.5 ms to 60 ms, and five sampling rates from 8 kHz (with 4 kHz bandwidth) to 48 kHz (with 20 kHz bandwidth, the human hearing range).
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] An Opus stream can support up to 255 audio channels, and it allows channel coupling between channels in groups of two using mid-side coding.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In any Opus stream, the bitrate, bandwidth, and delay can be continually varied without introducing any distortion or discontinuity; mixing packets from different streams will cause a smooth non-intrusive change, rather than the distortion common in other codecs.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Unlike Vorbis, Opus does not require large codebooks for each individual file, making it relatively more efficient and resilient for short clips of audio.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In Opus, both were modified to support more frame sizes, as well as further algorithmic improvements and integration, such as using CELT's range encoder for both types.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] To minimize overhead at low bitrates, if latency is not as pressing, SILK has support for packing multiple 20 ms frames together, sharing context and headers; SILK also allows Low Bitrate Redundancy (LBRR) frames, allowing low-quality packet loss recovery.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] CELT includes both spectral replication and noise generation, similar to AAC's SBR and PNS, and can further save bits by filtering out all harmonics of tonal sounds entirely, then replicating them in the decoder.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Better tone detection is an ongoing project to improve quality.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The format has three different modes: speech, hybrid, and CELT.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] When compressing speech, SILK is used for audio frequencies up to 8 kHz.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] If wider bandwidth is desired, a hybrid mode uses CELT to encode the frequency range above 8 kHz.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The third mode is pure-CELT, designed for general audio.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] SILK is inherently VBR and cannot hit a bitrate target, while CELT can always be encoded to any specific number of bytes, enabling hybrid and CELT mode when CBR is required.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] SILK supports frame sizes of 10, 20, 40 and 60 ms.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] CELT supports frame sizes of 2.5, 5, 10 and 20 ms.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Thus, hybrid mode only supports frame sizes of 10 and 20 ms; frames shorter than 10 ms will always use CELT mode.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] A typical Opus packet contains a single frame, but packets of up to 120 ms are produced by combining multiple frames per packet.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus can transparently switch between modes, frame sizes, bandwidths, and channel counts on a per-packet basis, although specific applications may choose to limit this.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The reference implementation is written in C and compiles on hardware architectures with or without a floating-point unit, although floating-point is currently required for audio bandwidth detection (dynamic switching between SILK, CELT, and hybrid encoding) and most speed optimizations.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus packets are not self-delimiting, but are designed to be used inside a container of some sort which supplies the decoder with each packet's length.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus was originally specified for encapsulation in Ogg containers, specified as `audio/ogg; codecs=opus`, and for Ogg Opus files the `.opus` filename extension is recommended.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus streams are also supported in Matroska, WebM, MPEG-TS, and MP4.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Alternatively, each Opus packet may be wrapped in a network packet which supplies the packet length.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus packets may be sent over an ordered datagram protocol such as RTP.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] An optional self-delimited packet format is defined in an appendix to the specification.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] This uses one or two additional bytes per packet to encode the packet length, allowing packets to be concatenated without encapsulation.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus allows the following bandwidths during encoding.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus compression does not depend on the input sample rate; timestamps are measured in 48 kHz units even if the full bandwidth is not used.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Likewise, the output sample rate may be freely chosen.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] For example, audio can be input at 16 kHz yet be set to encode only narrowband audio.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Version 1.6 introduced an experimental build flag that enables a feature known as Opus HD, allowing sampling rates of up to 96 kHz for non-audio purposes.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus was proposed for the standardization of a new audio format at the IETF, which was eventually accepted and granted by the *codec* working group.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] It is based on two initially separate standard proposals from the Xiph.Org Foundation and Skype Technologies S.A.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Its main developers are Jean-Marc Valin (Xiph.Org, Octasic, Mozilla Corporation, Amazon), Koen Vos (Skype), and Timothy B.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Terriberry (Xiph.Org, Mozilla Corporation, Amazon).
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Among others, Juin-Hwey (Raymond) Chen (Broadcom), Gregory Maxwell (Xiph.Org, Wikimedia), and Chris Montgomery (Xiph.Org) were also involved.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The development of the CELT part of the format originated from discussions on a successor for Vorbis under the working name *Ghost*.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] As a newer speech codec from the Xiph.Org Foundation, Opus replaces Xiph's older speech codec Speex, an earlier project of Jean-Marc Valin.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] CELT has been worked on since November 2007.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The SILK part has been under development at Skype since January 2007 as the successor of their SVOPC, an internal project to make the company independent from third-party codecs like iSAC and iLBC and respective license payments.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In March 2009, Skype suggested the development and standardization of a wideband audio format within the IETF.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Nearly a year passed with much debate on the formation of an appropriate working group.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] (Some of the opponents would later claim patent rights that Xiph dismissed; see below.) The working group finally formed in February 2010, and even the corresponding Study Group 16 from the ITU-T pledged to support its work.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In July 2010, a prototype of a hybrid format was presented that combined the two proposed format candidates SILK and CELT.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In September 2010, Opus was submitted to the IETF as proposal for standardization.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] For a short time the format went under the name of *Harmony* before it got its present name in October 2010.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] At the beginning of February 2011, the bitstream format was tentatively frozen, subject to last changes.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Near the end of July 2011, Jean-Marc Valin was hired by the Mozilla Corporation to continue working on Opus.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In November 2011, the working group issued the last call for changes on the bitstream format.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The bitstream has been frozen since January 8, 2012.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] On July 2, 2012, Opus was approved by the IETF for standardization.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The reference software entered release candidate state on August 8, 2012.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The final specification was released as RFC 6716 on September 10, 2012. and versions 1.0 and 1.0.1 of the reference implementation libopus were released the day after.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] On July 11, 2013, libopus 1.0.3 brought bug fixes and a new surround sound API that improves channel allocation and quality, especially for LFE.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Two new VBR modes were added: unconstrained for more consistent quality, and temporal VBR that boosts louder frames and generally improves quality.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] libopus 1.1.1 was released on November 26, 2015, and 1.1.2 on January 12, 2016, both adding speed optimizations and bug fixes.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] July 15, 2016 saw the release of version 1.1.3 and includes bug fixes, optimizations, documentation updates and experimental Ambisonics work.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] libopus 1.2 Beta was released on May 24, 2017. libopus 1.2 was released on June 20, 2017.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Improvements brought in 1.2 allow it to create fullband music at bitrates as low as 32 kbit/s, and wideband speech at just 12 kbit/s.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] libopus 1.2 includes optional support for the decoder specification changes made in drafts of RFC 8251, improving the quality of output from such low-rate streams.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] libopus 1.3 was released on October 18, 2018.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The Opus 1.3 major release again brings quality improvements, new features, and bug fixes.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] This Opus 1.3.1 minor release fixes an issue with the analysis on files with digital silence (all zeros), especially on x87 builds (mostly affects 32-bit builds).
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] libopus 1.4 was released on April 20, 2023.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] libopus 1.5 was released on March 4, 2024.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] libopus 1.6 was released on December 15, 2025.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The current focus is on adding a deep learning based redundancy encoder that enhances packet loss concealment by embedding one second of recovery data in each encoded packet.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] This encoder is a backwards compatible change to the codec enabling customers to easily upgrade applications to take advantage of this machine learning capability.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] A draft RFC is underway to standardize the new capability.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] This RFC is one of the first attempts to standardize a deep learning algorithm in the IETF.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus performs relatively well at both low and high bitrates.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In listening tests around 64 kbit/s, Opus shows superior quality compared to HE-AAC codecs, which were previously dominant due to their use of the patented spectral band replication (SBR) technology.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In listening tests around 96 kbit/s, Opus shows slightly superior quality compared to AAC and significantly better quality compared to Vorbis and MP3.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus has very low algorithmic delay, a necessity for use as part of a low-audio-latency communication link, which can permit natural conversation, networked music performances, or lip sync at live events.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Total one-way latency below 150 ms is the preferred target of most VoIP systems to enable natural conversation with turn-taking little affected by delay.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Musicians typically feel in-time with up to around 30 ms audio latency, roughly in accord with the fusion time of the Haas effect, though matching playback delay of each user's own instrument to the round-trip latency can also help.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] It is suggested for lip sync that around 45–100 ms audio latency may be acceptable.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus permits trading-off reduced quality or increased bitrate to achieve an even smaller algorithmic delay (5.0 ms minimum).
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] While the reference implementation's default Opus frame is 20.0 ms long, the SILK layer requires a further 5.0 ms lookahead plus 1.5 ms for resampling, giving a default delay of 26.5 ms.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] When the CELT layer is active, it requires 2.5 ms lookahead for window overlap to which a matching delay of 4.0 ms is added by default to synchronize with the SILK layer.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] If the encoder is instantiated in the special *restricted low delay* mode, the 4.0 ms matching delay is removed and the SILK layer is disabled, permitting the minimal algorithmic delay of 5.0 ms.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The format and algorithms are openly documented and the reference implementation is published as free software.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Xiph's reference implementation is called *libopus* and a package called *opus-tools* provides command-line encoder and decoder utilities.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] It is published under the terms of a BSD-like license.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] It is written in C and can be compiled for hardware architectures with or without a floating-point unit.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The accompanying diagnostic tool *opusinfo* reports detailed technical information about Opus files, including information on the standard compliance of the bitstream format.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] It is based on *ogginfo* from the *vorbis-tools* and therefore — unlike the encoder and decoder — is available under the terms of version 2 of the GPL.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] RFC 6716 contains a complete source code for an older version of the reference implementation written in C.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Libopus is the more up-to-date but non-normative branch of the reference implementation.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The FFmpeg project has encoder and decoder implementations not derived from the reference library.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The documentation describes it as CELT-only and poorer-quality than the reference.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The libopus reference library has been ported to C#, Java and Go as part of a project called Concentus.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] These ports sacrifice performance for the sake of being easily integrated into cross-platform applications.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Digital Radio Mondiale – a digital radio format for AM frequencies – can broadcast and receive Opus audio (albeit not recognised in official standard) using Dream software-defined radio.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The Wikimedia Foundation sponsored a free and open source online JavaScript Opus encoder for browsers supporting the required HTML5 features.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] A list of radio stations that stream using Opus audio codec can be found on the Xiph.Org Foundation Icecast directory.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In late 2014 and 2015, Google's video platform YouTube started offering Opus audio along with VP9 video in the WebM file format, through DASH streaming.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In July 2024, YouTube rolled out an additional high quality audio format option, 256 kbit/s Opus, to YouTube Music Premium subscribers.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Since 2016, WhatsApp has been using Opus as its audio file format.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Signal switched from Speex to Opus audio codec for better audio quality in the beginning of 2017.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In 2018, SoundCloud switched from MP3 to Opus, reducing half of its required bandwidth for music streaming.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In January 2021, Vimeo introduced Opus to its video platform.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In 2021, the Danish journalism website Zetland switched from MP3 to Opus for its articles' audio recordings, which attained a 35 percent reduction in bandwidth and reduced climate footprint.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Most end-user software relies on multimedia frameworks provided by the operating system.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Native Opus codec support is implemented in most major multimedia frameworks for Unix-like operating systems, including GStreamer, FFmpeg, and Libav libraries.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The WebM container `.webm` is mostly used on online video platforms (e.g.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] YouTube), and is usually treated as a video file by operating systems & media players.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Even if a WebM file contains only Opus audio and no video, some music players do not recognize WebM files as audio files and do not support reading of file metadata.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The Ogg container `.opus` is preferred for audio-only files, and most media players have support for audio file metadata tagged in the Vorbis comment format.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Google added native support for Opus audio playback in Android 5.0 "Lollipop".
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] However, it was limited to Opus audio encapsulated in Matroska and WebM containers, such as `.mkv`, `.mka` and `.webm` files.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Android 7.0 "Nougat" introduced support for Opus audio encapsulated in Ogg containers.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Android 10 finally added native support for `.opus` extensions.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Safari 18.4 added support for Opus and Vorbis codecs with Ogg containers when using macOS Sequoia 15.4 or iOS 18.4 and later.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] On Windows 10, version 1607, Microsoft provided native support for Opus audio encapsulated in Matroska and WebM containers.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] On version 1709, support for Opus audio encapsulated in Ogg containers was made available through a pre-installed add-on called Web Media Extensions.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] On Windows 10 version 1903, native support for the `.opus` extension was added.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] On Windows 8.1 and older, third-party decoders, such as LAV Filters, are available to provide support for the format.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] iOS 17 includes support for natively encoding and decoding the Opus codec through the operating system's AudioToolbox framework.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Playback of Ogg files in the `.opus` container is supported through the Files application.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus is additionally supported within the Core Audio Format `.caf` container, the QuickTime `.mov` container, and the ISOBMFF or MP4 file format `.mp4` container.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] As the AudioToolbox framework is shared with macOS, similar support should be present in both operating systems as they further develop.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] In 2024, Apple Podcasts does not support Opus.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] While support in multimedia frameworks automatically enables Opus support in software which is built on top of such frameworks, several applications developers made additional efforts for supporting the Opus audio format in their software.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Streaming Icecast radio trials are live since September 2012 and January 2013.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] SteamOS uses Opus or Vorbis for streaming audio.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus support is mandatory for WebRTC implementations.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus is supported in Mozilla Firefox, Chromium and Google Chrome, Blink-based Opera, as well as all browsers for Unix-like systems relying on GStreamer for multimedia formats support.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Although Internet Explorer will not provide Opus playback natively, support for the format is built into the Edge browser, along with VP9, for full WebM support.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Safari supports Opus as of iOS 11 and macOS High Sierra.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Due to its abilities, Opus gained early interest from voice over IP (VoIP) software vendors.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Several SIP clients, including Acrobits Softphone, CSipSimple (via additional plug-in), Empathy (via GStreamer), Jitsi, Tuenti, Line2 (currently only on iOS), Linphone, Phoner and PhonerLite, SFLphone, Telephone, Mumble, Discord and TeamSpeak 3 voice chat software also support Opus.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] TrueConf supports Opus in its VoIP products.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Asterisk lacked builtin Opus support for legal reasons, but a third-party patch was available for download and official support via a binary blob was added in September 2016.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Tox P2P videoconferencing software uses Opus exclusively.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Classified-ads distributed messaging app sends raw opus frames inside TLS socket in its VoIP implementation.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus is widely used as the voice codec in WhatsApp, which has over 1.5 billion users worldwide.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] WhatsApp uses Opus at 8–16 kHz sampling rates, with the Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP).
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The PlayStation 4 video game console also uses the CELT/Opus codec for its PlayStation Network system party chat.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The Source Engine uses Opus for its voice chat system.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] It is also used in the Zoom videoconferencing app.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Since version 3.13, Rockbox enables Opus playback on supported portable media players, including some products from the iPod series by Apple, devices made by iriver, Archos and Sandisk, and on Android devices using "Rockbox as an Application".
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] All recent Grandstream IP phones support Opus audio both for encoding and decoding.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] OBihai OBi1062, OBi1032 and OBi1022 IP phones all support Opus.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Recent BlueSound wireless speakers support Opus playback.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Devices running Hiby OS, like the Hiby R3, are capable of decoding Opus files natively.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Many broadcast IP codecs include Opus such as those manufactured by Comrex, GatesAir and Tieline.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The Sony PlayStation 5 supports capturing 1080p and 2160p footage using VP9 video and Opus audio in a WebM container.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Android 13 supports Opus as a bluetooth headphone (A2DP) codec, motivated by its low latency, which is important for head-tracked spatial audio.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Google's Pixel Buds Pro supports this A2DP codec.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] As an open standard, the algorithms are openly documented, and a reference implementation (including the source code) is published.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Qualcomm, Huawei, France Telecom, and Ericsson have claimed that their patents may apply, which Xiph's legal counsel denies, and none have pursued any legal action.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] The Opus license automatically and retroactively terminates for any entity that attempts to file a patent suit.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Vectis sells a package of patents pools which are claimed that apply to Opus codec.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Opus Patent Pool is managed by Vectis and contains a series of patents owned by Dolby, Fraunhofer and NTT.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Vectis have engaged in dispute against Epson and ended with an agreement.
[src:opus-codec/opus-audio-format] Actual legal dispute from Vectis are against Acer.
[src:opus-codec/perceptual-coding] Perceptual coding is based on models of human hearing and vision, such as those studied in psychoacoustics and psychovisual research.
[src:opus-codec/perceptual-coding] By discarding or reducing components of a signal that fall below perceptual thresholds, it achieves significant reductions in bit rate while maintaining a subjectively acceptable quality.
[src:opus-codec/perceptual-coding] The principles of perceptual coding were applied in analog communication systems long before the advent of digital media.
[src:opus-codec/perceptual-coding] These analog systems demonstrated the effectiveness of tailoring transmission to the characteristics of human perception, laying the groundwork for digital perceptual coding methods.
[src:opus-codec/perceptual-coding] Research in the 1970s and 1980s on psychoacoustics and psychovisual modeling provided the basis for digital perceptual coding.
[src:opus-codec/perceptual-coding] In audio, this led to the late-1980s development of the MPEG audio formats (such as MP3), which achieved major reductions in bit rate by discarding inaudible sound components.
[src:opus-codec/perceptual-coding] At the same time, the MPEG standards applied similar principles to video, using techniques such as chroma subsampling and motion-adaptive coding.
[src:opus-codec/perceptual-coding] During the 1990s and 2000s, perceptual coding was embedded in widely used formats including AAC, MPEG-2 video, and H.264/AVC, supporting the rise of digital media distribution on CDs, DVDs, and early internet platforms.
[src:opus-codec/perceptual-coding] More recent codecs, such as HEVC, AV1, and Opus, continue to refine perceptual models to balance compression efficiency with quality on modern networks and devices.
[src:opus-codec/perceptual-coding] Perceptual coding draws directly on psychoacoustics (the study of auditory perception) and psychovisual research (the study of visual perception).
[src:opus-codec/perceptual-coding] These disciplines provide the models that determine which parts of a signal can be safely removed without affecting perceived quality.
[src:opus-codec/speex] The **Speex** project is an attempt to create a free software speech codec, unencumbered by patent restrictions.
[src:opus-codec/speex] Speex is licensed under the BSD License and is used with the Xiph.org Foundation's Ogg container format.
[src:opus-codec/speex] The Speex coder uses the Ogg bitstream format, and the Speex designers see their project as complementary to the Vorbis general-purpose audio compression project.
[src:opus-codec/speex] Since 2012, the developers of Speex have considered it to be obsoleted by Opus.
[src:opus-codec/speex] Unlike many other speech codecs, Speex is not targeted at cell phones but rather at voice over IP (VoIP) and file-based compression.
[src:opus-codec/speex] The design goals have been to make a codec that would allow both very good quality speech and low bit rate, which led to the development of a codec with multiple bit rates.
[src:opus-codec/speex] Very good quality also meant the support of wideband (16 kHz sampling rate) in addition to narrowband (telephone quality, 8 kHz sampling rate).
[src:opus-codec/speex] Designing for VoIP instead of cell phone use means that Speex must be robust to lost packets, but not to corrupted ones since UDP ensures that packets either arrive unaltered or don't arrive.
[src:opus-codec/speex] All this led to the choice of Code Excited Linear Prediction (CELP) as the encoding technique to use for Speex.
[src:opus-codec/speex] One of the main reasons is that CELP has long proved that it could do the job and scale well to both low bit rates (as evidenced by DoD CELP @ 4.8 kbit/s) and high bit rates (as with G.728 @ 16 kbit/s).
[src:opus-codec/speex] Speex is mainly designed for 3 different sampling rates: 8 kHz (narrowband), 16 kHz (wideband) and 32 kHz (ultra-wideband).
[src:opus-codec/speex] Speex encoding is controlled most of the time by a quality parameter that ranges from 0 to 10.
[src:opus-codec/speex] In constant bit-rate (CBR) operation, the quality parameter is an integer, while for variable bit-rate (VBR), the parameter is a float.
[src:opus-codec/speex] With Speex, it is possible to vary the complexity allowed for the encoder.
[src:opus-codec/speex] This is done by controlling how the search is performed with an integer ranging from 1 to 10 in a way that's similar to the -1 to -9 options to gzip and bzip2 compression utilities.
[src:opus-codec/speex] For normal use, the noise level at complexity 1 is between 1 and 2 dB higher than at complexity 10, but the CPU requirements for complexity 10 is about 5 times higher than for complexity 1.
[src:opus-codec/speex] In practice, the best trade-off is between complexity 2 and 4, though higher settings are often useful when encoding non-speech sounds like DTMF tones.
[src:opus-codec/speex] Variable bit-rate (VBR) allows a codec to change its bit rate dynamically to adapt to the "difficulty" of the audio being encoded.
[src:opus-codec/speex] In the example of Speex, sounds like vowels and high-energy transients require a higher bit rate to achieve good quality, while fricatives (e.g. s and f sounds) can be coded adequately with fewer bits.
[src:opus-codec/speex] For this reason, VBR can achieve lower bit rate for the same quality, or a better quality for a certain bit rate.
[src:opus-codec/speex] Despite its advantages, VBR has two main drawbacks: first, by only specifying quality, there's no guarantee about the final average bit-rate.
[src:opus-codec/speex] Second, for some real-time applications like voice over IP (VoIP), what counts is the maximum bit-rate, which must be low enough for the communication channel.
[src:opus-codec/speex] Average bit-rate solves one of the problems of VBR, as it dynamically adjusts VBR quality in order to meet a specific target bit-rate.
[src:opus-codec/speex] Because the quality/bit-rate is adjusted in real-time (open-loop), the global quality will be slightly lower than that obtained by encoding in VBR with exactly the right quality setting to meet the target average bitrate.
[src:opus-codec/speex] When enabled, voice activity detection detects whether the audio being encoded is speech or silence/background noise.
[src:opus-codec/speex] VAD is always implicitly activated when encoding in VBR, so the option is only useful in non-VBR operation.
[src:opus-codec/speex] In this case, Speex detects non-speech periods and encode them with just enough bits to reproduce the background noise.
[src:opus-codec/speex] This is called "comfort noise generation" (CNG).
[src:opus-codec/speex] Discontinuous transmission is an addition to VAD/VBR operation, that allows to stop transmitting completely when the background noise is stationary.
[src:opus-codec/speex] In file-based operation, only 5 bits are used for such frames (corresponding to 250 kbit/s) since the process that is writing to the file cannot be stopped.
[src:opus-codec/speex] Perceptual enhancement is a part of the decoder which, when turned on, tries to reduce (the perception of) the noise produced by the coding/decoding process.
[src:opus-codec/speex] In most cases, perceptual enhancement makes the sound further from the original objectively (signal-to-noise ratio), but in the end it still sounds better (subjective improvement).
[src:opus-codec/speex] Every speech codec introduces a delay in the transmission.
[src:opus-codec/speex] For Speex, this delay is equal to the frame size, plus some amount of "look-ahead" required to process each frame.
[src:opus-codec/speex] In narrowband operation (8 kHz), the delay is 30 ms, while for wideband (16 kHz), the delay is 34 ms.
[src:opus-codec/speex] These values don't account for the CPU time it takes to encode or decode the frames.
[src:opus-codec/speex] There is already a large base of applications supporting the speex codec, from teleconference software to streaming, P2P, and audio processing applications.
[src:opus-codec/speex] Most of these are based on the DirectDS filter, OpenACM codec -- Netmeeting on Microsoft Windows, or OpenH323 on Linux (GnomeMeeting), for example.
[src:opus-codec/speex] There are also plugins for the Winamp and XMMS players.
[src:opus-codec/speex] The MIME type for Speex is audio/x-speex, although the type audio/speex is proposed.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP technology has evolved to integrate with mobile telephony, including Voice over LTE (VoLTE) and Voice over NR (Vo5G), enabling seamless voice communication over mobile data networks.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] These advancements have extended VoIP's role beyond its traditional use in Internet-based applications.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] It has become a key component of modern mobile infrastructure, as 4G and 5G networks rely entirely on this technology for voice transmission.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The steps and principles involved in originating VoIP telephone calls are similar to traditional digital telephony and involve signaling, channel setup, digitization of the analog voice signals, and encoding.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Instead of being transmitted over a circuit-switched network, the digital information is packetized and transmission occurs as IP packets over a packet-switched network.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] They transport media streams using special media delivery protocols that encode audio and video with audio codecs and video codecs.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Various codecs exist that optimize the media stream based on application requirements and network bandwidth; some implementations rely on narrowband and compressed speech, while others support high-fidelity stereo codecs.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The most widely used speech coding standards in VoIP are based on the linear predictive coding (LPC) and modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) compression methods.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Popular codecs include the MDCT-based AAC-LD (used in FaceTime), the LPC/MDCT-based Opus (used in WhatsApp), the LPC-based SILK (used in Skype), μ-law, A-law versions of G.711, G.722, an open source voice codec known as iLBC, and a codec that uses only 8 kbit/s each way called G.729.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Early providers of voice-over-IP services used business models and offered technical solutions that mirrored the architecture of the legacy telephone network.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Second-generation providers, such as Skype, built closed networks for private user bases, offering the benefit of free calls and convenience while potentially charging for access to other communication networks, such as the PSTN.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] This limited the freedom of users to mix-and-match third-party hardware and software.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Third-generation providers, such as Google Talk, adopted the concept of federated VoIP.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] These solutions typically allow dynamic interconnection between users in any two domains of the Internet, when a user wishes to place a call.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In addition to VoIP phones, VoIP is also available on many personal computers and other Internet access devices.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Calls and SMS text messages may be sent via Wi-Fi or the carrier's mobile data network.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP provides a framework for consolidation of all modern communications technologies using a single unified communications system.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP technology has been adapted for use in mobile networks, leading to the development of advanced systems designed to support voice communication over modern data infrastructures.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Among these are Voice over LTE (VoLTE) and Voice over 5G (Vo5G), which enable voice communication over IP-based mobile infrastructures.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In contrast to traditional VoIP services, which often function independently of global telephone numbering systems, VoLTE and Vo5G are directly connected to mobile operators' infrastructures, providing seamless connectivity to the international telephone network.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoLTE, introduced as part of 4G LTE networks, enables voice communication over an IP-based infrastructure initially developed for data transmission.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] It offers features such as high-definition voice (HD Voice) and faster call setup times compared to circuit-switched networks.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Vo5G, the 5G equivalent of VoLTE, utilizes the increased speed, reduced latency, and greater capacity of 5G networks to further enhance these capabilities.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Both VoLTE and Vo5G maintain compatibility with traditional public switched telephone networks (PSTNs), allowing users to make and receive calls to and from any telephone number worldwide.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] These technologies differ from standalone VoIP services by being fully integrated with mobile network operators.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] This integration ensures additional features such as emergency call support and quality-of-service guarantees, making them a central part of modern mobile telecommunication systems.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice over IP has been implemented with proprietary protocols and protocols based on open standards in applications such as VoIP phones, mobile applications, and web-based communications.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] A variety of functions are needed to implement VoIP communication.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Some protocols perform multiple functions, while others perform only a few and must be used in concert.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Mass-market VoIP services use existing broadband Internet access, by which subscribers place and receive telephone calls in much the same manner as they would via the PSTN.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Full-service VoIP phone companies provide inbound and outbound service with direct inbound dialing.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Many offer unlimited domestic calling and sometimes international calls for a flat monthly subscription fee.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Phone calls between subscribers of the same provider are usually free when flat-fee service is not available.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] A VoIP phone is necessary to connect to a VoIP service provider.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] It is increasingly common for telecommunications providers to use VoIP telephony over dedicated and public IP networks as a backhaul to connect switching centers and to interconnect with other telephony network providers; this is often referred to as *IP backhaul*.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Smartphones may have SIP clients built into the firmware or available as an application download.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Because of the bandwidth efficiency and low costs that VoIP technology can provide, businesses are migrating from traditional copper-wire telephone systems to VoIP systems to reduce their monthly phone costs.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In 2008, 80% of all new Private branch exchange (PBX) lines installed internationally were VoIP.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] For example, in the United States, the Social Security Administration is converting its field offices of 63,000 workers from traditional phone installations to a VoIP infrastructure carried over its existing data network.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP allows both voice and data communications to be run over a single network, which can significantly reduce infrastructure costs.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The prices of extensions on VoIP are lower than for PBX and key systems.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP switches may run on commodity hardware, such as personal computers.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Rather than closed architectures, these devices rely on standard interfaces.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP devices have simple, intuitive user interfaces, so users can often make simple system configuration changes.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Dual-mode phones enable users to continue their conversations as they move between an outside cellular service and an internal Wi-Fi network, so that it is no longer necessary to carry both a desktop phone and a cell phone.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Maintenance becomes simpler as there are fewer devices to oversee.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP solutions aimed at businesses have evolved into unified communications services that treat all communications—phone calls, faxes, voice mail, e-mail, web conferences, and more—as discrete units that can all be delivered via any means and to any handset, including cellphones.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Two kinds of service providers are operating in this space: one set is focused on VoIP for medium to large enterprises, while another is targeting the small-to-medium business (SMB) market.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Skype, which originally marketed itself as a service among friends, began to cater to businesses in 2009, providing free-of-charge connections between any users on the Skype network and connecting to and from ordinary PSTN telephones for a charge.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In general, the provision of VoIP telephony systems to organizational or individual users can be divided into two primary delivery methods: private or on-premises solutions, or externally hosted solutions delivered by third-party providers.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] On-premises delivery methods are more akin to the classic PBX deployment model for connecting an office to local PSTN networks.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] While many use cases still remain for private or on-premises VoIP systems, the wider market has been gradually shifting toward *Cloud* or *Hosted* VoIP solutions.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Hosted systems are also generally better suited to smaller or personal use VoIP deployments, where a private system may not be viable for these scenarios.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Typically, this will be one or more data centers with geographic relevance to the end-user(s) of the system.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] This infrastructure is external to the user of the system and is deployed and maintained by the service provider.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Endpoints, such as VoIP telephones or softphone applications (apps running on a computer or mobile device), will connect to the VoIP service remotely.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] These connections typically take place over public internet links, such as local fixed WAN breakout or mobile carrier service.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In the case of a private VoIP system, the primary telephony system itself is located within the private infrastructure of the end-user organization.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Usually, the system will be deployed on-premises at a site within the direct control of the organization.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] This can provide numerous benefits in terms of QoS control (see below), cost scalability, and ensuring privacy and security of communications traffic.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] However, the responsibility for ensuring that the VoIP system remains performant and resilient is predominantly vested in the end-user organization.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] This is not the case with a Hosted VoIP solution.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Private VoIP systems can be physical hardware PBX appliances, converged with other infrastructure, or they can be deployed as software applications.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Generally, the latter two options will be in the form of a separate virtualized appliance.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] However, in some scenarios, these systems are deployed on bare metal infrastructure or IoT devices.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] With some solutions, such as 3CX, companies can attempt to blend the benefits of hosted and private on-premises systems by implementing their own private solution but within an external environment.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Examples can include data center collocation services, public cloud, or private cloud locations.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] For on-premises systems, local endpoints within the same location typically connect directly over the LAN.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] For remote and external endpoints, available connectivity options mirror those of Hosted or Cloud VoIP solutions.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] However, VoIP traffic to and from the on-premises systems can often also be sent over secure private links.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Examples include personal VPN, site-to-site VPN, private networks such as MPLS and SD-WAN, or via private SBCs (Session Border Controllers).
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] While exceptions and private peering options do exist, it is generally uncommon for those private connectivity methods to be provided by Hosted or Cloud VoIP providers.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Communication on the IP network is perceived as less reliable in contrast to the circuit-switched public telephone network because it does not provide a network-based mechanism to ensure that data packets are not lost, and are delivered in sequential order.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] It is a best-effort network without fundamental quality of service (QoS) guarantees.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice, and all other data, travels in packets over IP networks with fixed maximum capacity.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Therefore, VoIP implementations may face problems with latency, packet loss, and jitter.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] By default, network routers handle traffic on a first-come, first-served basis.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Fixed delays cannot be controlled as they are caused by the physical distance the packets travel.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] They are especially problematic when satellite circuits are involved because of the long distance to a geostationary satellite and back; delays of 400–600 ms are typical.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Latency can be minimized by marking voice packets as being delay-sensitive with QoS methods such as DiffServ.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Network routers on high-volume traffic links may introduce latency that exceeds permissible thresholds for VoIP.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Excessive load on a link can cause congestion and associated queueing delays and packet loss.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] This signals a transport protocol like TCP to reduce its transmission rate to alleviate the congestion.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] But VoIP usually uses UDP, not TCP, because recovering from congestion through retransmission usually entails too much latency.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] So QoS mechanisms can avoid the undesirable loss of VoIP packets by immediately transmitting them ahead of any queued bulk traffic on the same link, even when the link is congested by bulk traffic.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP endpoints usually have to wait for the completion of transmission of previous packets before new data may be sent.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Although it is possible to preempt (abort) a less important packet in mid-transmission, this is not commonly done, especially on high-speed links where transmission times are short even for maximum-sized packets.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] An alternative to preemption on slower links, such as dialup and digital subscriber line (DSL), is to reduce the maximum transmission time by reducing the maximum transmission unit.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] But since every packet must contain protocol headers, this increases relative header overhead on every link traversed.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The receiver must resequence IP packets that arrive out of order and recover gracefully when packets arrive too late or not at all.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Packet delay variation results from changes in queuing delay along a given network path due to competition from other users for the same transmission links.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP receivers accommodate this variation by storing incoming packets briefly in a playout buffer, deliberately increasing latency to improve the chance that each packet will be on hand when it is time for the voice engine to play it.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The added delay is thus a compromise between excessive latency and excessive dropout, i.e., momentary audio interruptions.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Although jitter is a random variable, it is the sum of several other random variables that are at least somewhat independent: the individual queuing delays of the routers along the Internet path in question.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Motivated by the central limit theorem, jitter can be modeled as a Gaussian random variable.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] This suggests continually estimating the mean delay and its standard deviation and setting the playout delay so that only packets delayed more than several standard deviations above the mean will arrive too late to be useful.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In practice, the variance in latency of many Internet paths is dominated by a small number (often one) of relatively slow and congested bottleneck links.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Most Internet backbone links are now so fast (e.g., 10 Gbit/s) that their delays are dominated by the transmission medium (e.g., optical fiber) and the routers driving them do not have enough buffering for queuing delays to be significant.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] A number of protocols have been defined to support the reporting of quality of service (QoS) and quality of experience (QoE) for VoIP calls.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] These include RTP Control Protocol (RTCP) extended reports, SIP RTCP summary reports, H.460.9 Annex B (for H.323), H.248.30 and MGCP extensions.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP metrics reports are exchanged between IP endpoints on an occasional basis during a call, and an end-of-call message is sent via SIP RTCP summary report or one of the other signaling protocol extensions.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP metrics reports are intended to support real-time feedback related to QoS problems, the exchange of information between the endpoints for improved call quality calculation and a variety of other applications.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] DSL modems typically provide Ethernet connections to local equipment, but inside they may actually be Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) modems.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] They use ATM Adaptation Layer 5 (AAL5) to segment each Ethernet packet into a series of 53-byte ATM cells for transmission, reassembling them back into Ethernet frames at the receiving end.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Using a separate virtual circuit identifier (VCI) for voice over IP has the potential to reduce latency on shared connections.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] ATM's potential for latency reduction is greatest on slow links because worst-case latency decreases with increasing link speed.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] A full-size (1500 byte) Ethernet frame takes 94 ms to transmit at 128 kbit/s but only 8 ms at 1.5 Mbit/s.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] If this is the bottleneck link, this latency is probably small enough to ensure good VoIP performance without MTU reductions or multiple ATM VCs.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The latest generations of DSL, VDSL and VDSL2, carry Ethernet without intermediate ATM/AAL5 layers, and they generally support IEEE 802.1p priority tagging so that VoIP can be queued ahead of less time-critical traffic.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] ATM has substantial header overhead: 5/53 = 9.4%, roughly twice the total header overhead of a 1500-byte Ethernet frame.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] This *ATM tax* is incurred by every DSL user, whether or not they take advantage of multiple virtual circuits – and few can.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Several protocols are used in the data link layer and physical layer for quality-of-service mechanisms that help VoIP applications work well even in the presence of network congestion.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The quality of voice transmission is characterized by several metrics that may be monitored by network elements and by the user agent hardware or software.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Such metrics include network packet loss, packet jitter, packet latency (delay), post-dial delay, and echo.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The metrics are determined by VoIP performance testing and monitoring.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] A VoIP media gateway controller (aka Class 5 Softswitch) works in cooperation with a media gateway (aka IP Business Gateway) and connects the digital media stream, so as to complete the path for voice and data.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Gateways include interfaces for connecting to standard PSTN networks.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Ethernet interfaces are also included in modern systems, which are specially designed to link calls that are passed via VoIP.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] E.164 is a global numbering standard for both the PSTN and public land mobile network (PLMN).
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Most VoIP implementations support E.164 to allow calls to be routed to and from VoIP subscribers and the PSTN/PLMN.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP implementations can also allow other identification techniques to be used.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] For example, Skype allows subscribers to choose *Skype names* (usernames) whereas SIP implementations can use Uniform Resource Identifier (URIs) similar to email addresses.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Often VoIP implementations employ methods of translating non-E.164 identifiers to E.164 numbers and vice versa, such as the Skype-In service provided by Skype and the E.164 number to URI mapping (ENUM) service in IMS and SIP.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Echo can also be an issue for PSTN integration.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Common causes of echo include impedance mismatches in analog circuitry and an acoustic path from the receive to transmit signal at the receiving end.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Local number portability (LNP) and mobile number portability (MNP) also impact VoIP business.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Number portability is a service that allows a subscriber to select a new telephone carrier without requiring a new number to be issued.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Typically, it is the responsibility of the former carrier to "map" the old number to the undisclosed number assigned by the new carrier.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] This is achieved by maintaining a database of numbers.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] A dialed number is initially received by the original carrier and quickly rerouted to the new carrier.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Multiple porting references must be maintained even if the subscriber returns to the original carrier.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) mandates carrier compliance with these consumer-protection stipulations.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In November 2007, the FCC in the United States released an order extending number portability obligations to interconnected VoIP providers and carriers that support VoIP providers.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] A voice call originating in the VoIP environment also faces least-cost routing (LCR) challenges to reach its destination if the number is routed to a mobile phone number on a traditional mobile carrier.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] LCR is based on checking the destination of each telephone call as it is made, and then sending the call via the network that will cost the customer the least.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] This rating is subject to some debate, given the complexity of call routing created by number portability.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] With MNP in place, LCR providers can no longer rely on using the network root prefix to determine how to route a call.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Instead, they must now determine the actual network of every number before routing the call.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Therefore, VoIP solutions also need to handle MNP when routing a voice call.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In countries without a central database, like the UK, it may be necessary to query the mobile network about which home network a mobile phone number belongs to.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] As the popularity of VoIP increases in the enterprise markets because of LCR options, VoIP needs to provide a certain level of reliability when handling calls.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] A telephone connected to a land line has a direct relationship between a telephone number and a physical location, which is maintained by the telephone company and available to emergency responders via the national emergency response service centers in the form of emergency subscriber lists.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] When an emergency call is received by a center, the location is automatically determined from its databases and displayed on the operator console.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In IP telephony, no such direct link between location and communications end point exists.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Even a provider having wired infrastructure, such as a DSL provider, may know only the approximate location of the device, based on the IP address allocated to the network router and the known service address.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Some ISPs do not track the automatic assignment of IP addresses to customer equipment.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] IP communication provides for device mobility.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] For example, a residential broadband connection may be used as a link to a virtual private network of a corporate entity, in which case the IP address being used for customer communications may belong to the enterprise, not the residential ISP.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Such off-premises extensions may appear as part of an upstream IP PBX.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] On mobile devices, e.g., a 3G handset or USB wireless broadband adapter, the IP address has no relationship with any physical location known to the telephony service provider, since a mobile user could be anywhere in a region with network coverage, even roaming via another cellular company.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] At the VoIP level, a phone or gateway may identify itself by its account credentials with a Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) registrar.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In such cases, the Internet telephony service provider (ITSP) knows only that a particular user's equipment is active.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Service providers often provide emergency response services by agreement with the user who registers a physical location and agrees that, if an emergency number is called from the IP device, emergency services are provided to that address only.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Such emergency services are provided by VoIP vendors in the United States by a system called Enhanced 911 (E911), based on the Wireless Communications and Public Safety Act.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The VoIP E911 emergency-calling system associates a physical address with the calling party's telephone number.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] All VoIP providers that provide access to the public switched telephone network are required to implement E911, a service for which the subscriber may be charged.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] "VoIP providers may not allow customers to opt out of 911 service." The VoIP E911 system is based on a static table lookup.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Unlike in cellular phones, where the location of an E911 call can be traced using assisted GPS or other methods, the VoIP E911 information is accurate only if subscribers keep their emergency address information current.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Sending faxes over VoIP networks is sometimes referred to as Fax over IP (FoIP).
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Transmission of fax documents was problematic in early VoIP implementations, as most voice digitization and compression codecs are optimized for the representation of the human voice and the proper timing of the modem signals cannot be guaranteed in a packet-based, connectionless network.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] A standards-based solution for reliably delivering fax-over-IP is the T.38 protocol.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The T.38 protocol is designed to compensate for the differences between traditional packet-less communications over analog lines and packet-based transmissions, which are the basis for IP communications.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The fax machine may be a standard device connected to an analog telephone adapter (ATA), or it may be a software application or dedicated network device operating via an Ethernet interface.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Originally, T.38 was designed to use UDP or TCP transmission methods across an IP network.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Some newer high-end fax machines have built-in T.38 capabilities, which are connected directly to a network switch or router.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In T.38 each packet contains a portion of the data stream sent in the previous packet.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Two successive packets have to be lost to actually lose data integrity.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Telephones for traditional residential analog service are usually connected directly to telephone company phone lines, which provide direct current to power most basic analog handsets independently of locally available electrical power.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP phones and VoIP telephone adapters connect to routers or cable modems, which typically depend on the availability of mains electricity or locally generated power.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Some VoIP service providers use customer premises equipment (e.g., cable modems) with battery-backed power supplies to assure uninterrupted service for up to several hours in case of local power failures.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Such battery-backed devices are typically designed for use with analog handsets.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Some VoIP service providers implement services to route calls to other telephone services of the subscriber, such as a cellular phone, in the event that the customer's network device is inaccessible to terminate the call.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Secure calls are possible using standardized protocols such as Secure Real-time Transport Protocol.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Most of the facilities for creating a secure telephone connection over traditional phone lines, such as digitizing and digital transmission, are already in place with VoIP.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] It is necessary only to encrypt and authenticate the existing data stream.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Automated software, such as a virtual PBX, may eliminate the need for personnel to greet and switch incoming calls.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The security concerns for VoIP telephone systems are similar to those of other Internet-connected devices.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] This means that hackers with knowledge of VoIP vulnerabilities can perform denial-of-service attacks, harvest customer data, record conversations, and compromise voicemail messages.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Compromised VoIP user account or session credentials may enable an attacker to incur substantial charges from third-party services, such as long-distance or international calling.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The technical details of many VoIP protocols create challenges in routing VoIP traffic through firewalls and network address translators, used to interconnect to transit networks or the Internet.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Private session border controllers are often employed to enable VoIP calls to and from protected networks.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Other methods to traverse NAT devices involve assistive protocols such as STUN and Interactive Connectivity Establishment (ICE).
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Standards for securing VoIP are available in the Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP) and the ZRTP protocol for analog telephony adapters, as well as for some softphones.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] IPsec is available to secure point-to-point VoIP at the transport level by using opportunistic encryption.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Though many consumer VoIP solutions do not support encryption of the signaling path or the media, securing a VoIP phone is conceptually easier to implement using VoIP than on traditional telephone circuits.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] A result of the lack of widespread support for encryption is that it is relatively easy to eavesdrop on VoIP calls when access to the data network is possible.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Free open-source solutions, such as Wireshark, facilitate capturing VoIP conversations.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Government and military organizations use various security measures to protect VoIP traffic, such as voice over secure IP (VoSIP), secure voice over IP (SVoIP), and secure voice over secure IP (SVoSIP).
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The distinction lies in whether encryption is applied in the telephone endpoint or in the network.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Secure voice over secure IP may be implemented by encrypting the media with protocols such as SRTP and ZRTP.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Secure voice over IP uses Type 1 encryption on a classified network, such as SIPRNet.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Public Secure VoIP is also available with free GNU software and in many popular commercial VoIP programs via libraries, such as ZRTP.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In June 2021, the National Security Agency (NSA) released comprehensive documents describing the four attack planes of a communications system – the network, perimeter, session controllers and endpoints – and explaining security risks and mitigation techniques for each of them.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice over IP protocols and equipment provide caller ID support that is compatible with the PSTN.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Many VoIP service providers also allow callers to configure custom caller ID information.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Wireline telephones which are manufactured in, imported to, or intended to be used in the US with Voice over IP service, on or after February 28, 2020, are required to meet the hearing aid compatibility requirements set forth by the Federal Communications Commission.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP has drastically reduced the cost of communication by sharing network infrastructure between data and voice.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] A single broadband connection has the ability to transmit multiple telephone calls.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] As the popularity of VoIP grows, governments are becoming more interested in regulating VoIP in a manner similar to PSTN services.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Throughout the developing world, particularly in countries where regulation is weak or captured by the dominant operator, restrictions on the use of VoIP are often imposed, including in Panama where VoIP is taxed, Guyana, where VoIP is prohibited.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In Ethiopia, where the government is nationalizing telecommunication service, it is a criminal offense to offer services using VoIP.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The country has installed firewalls to prevent international calls from being made using VoIP.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] These measures were taken after the popularity of VoIP reduced the income generated by the state-owned telecommunications company.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In Canada, the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission regulates telephone service, including VoIP telephony service.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP services operating in Canada are required to provide 9-1-1 emergency service.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] A general distinction is usually made between VoIP services that function over managed networks (via broadband connections) and VoIP services that function over unmanaged networks (essentially, the Internet).
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The relevant EU Directive is not clearly drafted concerning obligations that can exist independently of market power (e.g., the obligation to offer access to emergency calls), and it is impossible to say definitively whether VoIP service providers of either type are bound by them.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In Oman, it is illegal to provide or use unauthorized VoIP services, to the extent that websites of unlicensed VoIP providers have been blocked.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Violations may be punished with fines of 50,000 Omani Rial (about 130,317 US dollars), a two-year prison sentence or both.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In 2009, police raided 121 Internet cafes throughout the country and arrested 212 people for using or providing VoIP services.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In September 2017, Saudi Arabia lifted the ban on VoIPs, in an attempt to reduce operational costs and spur digital entrepreneurship.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In the United Arab Emirates (UAE), it is illegal to provide or use unauthorized VoIP services.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Websites of unlicensed VoIP providers have been blocked.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Some VoIP services, such as Skype, were allowed.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In January 2018, internet service providers in UAE blocked all VoIP apps, including Skype, but permitting only 2 government-approved VoIP apps (C'ME and BOTIM).
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In opposition, a petition on *Change.org* garnered over 5000 signatures, in response to which the website was blocked in UAE.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] On March 24, 2020, the United Arab Emirates loosened restrictions on VoIP services earlier prohibited in the country, to ease communication during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] However, popular instant messaging applications such as WhatsApp, Skype, and FaceTime remained blocked from being used for voice and video calls, constricting residents to use paid services from the country's state-owned telecom providers.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In India, it is legal to use VoIP, but it is illegal to have VoIP gateways inside India.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] This effectively means that people who have PCs can use them to make a VoIP call to other computers but not to a normal phone number.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Foreign-based VoIP server services are illegal to use in India.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Internet telephony is permitted to the ISP with restrictions.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] PC / a device / Adapter conforming to the standard of any international agencies like ITU or IETF, etc., in India to PSTN/PLMN abroad.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Any device / Adapter conforming to standards of International agencies like ITU, IETF etc., connected to ISP node with static IP address to similar device / Adapter; within or outside India.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Except whatever is described in condition (ii) above, no other form of Internet Telephony is permitted.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In India no Separate Numbering Scheme is provided to the Internet Telephony.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Presently the 10-digit Numbering allocation based on E.164 is permitted to the Fixed Telephony, GSM, CDMA wireless service.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] For Internet Telephony, the numbering scheme shall only conform to IP addressing Scheme of Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA).
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Translation of E.164 number / private number to IP address allotted to any device and vice versa, by ISP to show compliance with IANA numbering scheme is not permitted.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The Internet Service Licensee is not permitted to have PSTN/PLMN connectivity.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice communication to and from a telephone connected to PSTN/PLMN and following E.164 numbering is prohibited in India.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In South Korea, only providers registered with the government are authorized to offer VoIP services.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Unlike many VoIP providers, most of whom offer flat rates, Korean VoIP services are generally metered and charged at rates similar to terrestrial calling.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Foreign VoIP providers encounter high barriers to government registration.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] In the United States, the FCC requires all interconnected VoIP service providers to comply with requirements comparable to those for traditional telecommunications service providers.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP operators also receive the benefit of certain US telecommunications regulations, including an entitlement to interconnection and exchange of traffic with incumbent local exchange carriers via wholesale carriers.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Providers of *nomadic* VoIP service—those who are unable to determine the location of their users—are exempt from state telecommunications regulation.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] Another legal issue that the US Congress is debating concerns changes to the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The issue in question is calls between Americans and foreigners.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] The NSA is not authorized to tap Americans' conversations without a warrant—but the Internet, and specifically VoIP does not draw as clear a line to the location of a caller or a call's recipient as the traditional phone system does.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] As VoIP's low cost and flexibility convince more and more organizations to adopt the technology, surveillance for law enforcement agencies becomes more difficult.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP technology has also increased federal security concerns because VoIP and similar technologies have made it more difficult for the government to determine where a target is physically located when communications are being intercepted, and that creates a whole set of new legal challenges.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p02] Danny Cohen first demonstrated a form of packet voice in 1973 which was developed into Network Voice Protocol which operated across the early ARPANET.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p02] On the early ARPANET, real-time voice communication was not possible with uncompressed pulse-code modulation (PCM) digital speech packets, which had a bit rate of 64 kbps, much greater than the 2.4 kbps bandwidth of early modems.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p02] The solution to this problem was linear predictive coding (LPC), a speech coding data compression algorithm that was first proposed by Fumitada Itakura of Nagoya University and Shuzo Saito of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) in 1966.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p02] LPC was capable of speech compression down to 2.4 kbps, leading to the first successful real-time conversation over ARPANET in 1974, between Culler-Harrison Incorporated in Goleta, California, and MIT Lincoln Laboratory in Lexington, Massachusetts.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p02] LPC has since been the most widely used speech coding method.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p02] Code-excited linear prediction (CELP), a type of LPC algorithm, was developed by Manfred R.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p02] LPC algorithms remain an audio coding standard in modern VoIP technology.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p02] In the two decades following the 1974 demo, various forms of packet telephony were developed and industry interest groups formed to support the new technologies.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p02] Soon after it became an established area of interest in commercial labs of the major IT concerns, notably at AT&T, where Marian Croak and her team filed many patents related to the technology.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p02] By the late 1990s, the first softswitches became available, and new protocols, such as H.323, MGCP and Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) gained widespread attention.
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p02] In the early 2000s, the proliferation of high-bandwidth always-on Internet connections to residential dwellings and businesses spawned an industry of Internet telephony service providers (ITSPs).
[src:opus-codec/voice-over-ip-p02] The development of open-source telephony software, such as Asterisk PBX, fueled widespread interest and entrepreneurship in voice-over-IP services, applying new Internet technology paradigms, such as cloud services to telephony.
